          content_en: '**Groupthink** is a specific phenomenon described by psychologist Irving Janis after analyzing disasters like the Bay of Pigs invasion or the Challenger shuttle catastrophe. It works like this: a group wants to preserve harmony and cohesion. People with doubts suppress them (or voice them very mildly) and the group creates an illusion of agreement. A decision is made without critical debate — and it\'s often wrong.\n\nTypical signs of groupthink:\n- **Fast consensus** on a complex question,\n- **self-appointed guardians** of the group\'s morale ("we know how it is"),\n- **pressure** on anyone who\'d disagree,\n- **self-censorship** (people stay silent because they\'re not sure),\n- **illusion of unanimity** (silence is read as agreement).\n\nParadox: the **more cohesive** the group, the higher the risk of groupthink. Good friends on a team don\'t want to damage the relationships — and that\'s exactly the environment where the pressure for critical debate is missing.',
