          content_en: 'The third powerful principle is **scarcity**: "what\'s rare is valuable." The brain interprets shortage as a signal of value — evolutionarily it made sense (scarce food = more valuable). Today every other marketing campaign exploits it: **"last one," "today only," "ends in 3 hours," "limited edition."**\n\nScarcity works especially strongly combined with **time pressure**. Time pressure inhibits analytical thinking — the brain switches to "I have to decide now" mode and bypasses rational filters. That\'s exactly why salespeople push "you have to decide now, tomorrow it won\'t be there."\n\nDefense: the rule **"Did I want it yesterday?"** If the answer was "no," then "today\'s 50% discount" isn\'t a reason to buy — it\'s a trap. Genuinely good offers usually don\'t push so hard.',
