          content_en: '**Status** is your place in the social hierarchy — "how high" you stand in the group of people who matter to you. That could be family, coworkers, friends, a sports club, even an online discussion.\n\nTo the brain, status is almost as important as **physical survival**. There\'s an evolutionary reason: in our ancestors\' groups, higher status meant better access to food, protection, and mates. Whoever dropped in the hierarchy was really endangered — less food, less protection, lower chance of passing on genes. The brain still remembers this.\n\nThat\'s why your body reacts to **social** events as it would to **physical** ones. Humiliation, being ignored, being ridiculed in a group — all of it activates the same brain areas as physical pain (research has confirmed this repeatedly with fMRI). The brain **technically distinguishes** the two kinds of pain **very little**.',
